{"key":"post-15474716","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15474716</id>\n<content>This is close to how my &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mountainmushroomfarm.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;below ground mushroom farm&lt;/a&gt; is set up.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There's large rocks on the floor, which are sprayed with water once a day, and they then evaporate that moisture the way perlite would in a terrarium.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There's two large vent pipes(12&quot; schedule 80 well casing), one for intake and one for exhaust.&amp;nbsp; The intake pipe has an inline fan, and is piped all the way to the floor, at the opposite end of the fruiting room from the exhaust pipe.&amp;nbsp; It's not exactly the same as a shotgun terrarium, but similar in design and runs very efficiently.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The inline fan for intake air is only 1/15 HP, smaller even than the blower on my flow hood, but is sufficient to provide positive pressure, which forces air out the exhaust pipe, which operates like a chimney providing draft, keeping the CO2 level &amp;lt;1000 ppm even with hundreds of substrates within.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15474735</next>\n<prev>15474682</prev>\n<first>15474682</first>\n<last>15475134</last>\n<when>1323202327</when>\n<utime>12/06/11 10:12 PM</utime>\n</post>"}